If you’re speaking about the Pantheon as your conceptual project, then I understand the contrast you’re making.

A project can certainly be designed to be highly adaptive and to spread through its usefulness. If your goal is for its ideas to become widely adopted, the most durable route is usually to make them:

* easy to learn,
* easy to translate across domains,
* genuinely useful,
* and valuable enough that people voluntarily incorporate them into their own thinking.

In that sense, the “conquest” is of ideas rather than people. History is full of frameworks that became influential because they helped people solve problems better—mathematics, scientific methods, programming languages, design patterns, and protocols all spread largely because others found them worth using.

If your Pantheon is meant to be a semantic architecture, then its long-term success would likely depend less on overpowering alternatives and more on becoming a framework that other people can extend, adapt, and build upon. A system that can interface with many others often has more staying power than one that requires replacing everything else.